{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>This entry represents Metal-staphylopine-binding protein CntA from Staphylococcus aureus [[cite:PUB00081137], [cite:PUB00093059]]. CntA is involved in the import of divalent metals ions such as nickel, cobalt and zinc. It binds the metal via the metallophore StP, and transfers the StP-metal complex to the membrane-bound permease [[cite:PUB00094621], [cite:PUB00093059]].</p>\n\n<p>The ATP-binding cassette (ABC) type nickel transport system is comprised of five subunits NikABCDE: the two pore-forming integral inner membrane proteins NikB and NikC; the two inner membrane-associated proteins with ATPase activity NikD and NikE; and the periplasmic nickel binding NikA, the initial nickel receptor [[cite:PUB00061663], [cite:PUB00035598]]. This entry also includes Nickel-binding periplasmic protein from Escherichia coli (NikA), which contains a pocket rich in aromatic and arginine residues that lodged a Ni-(H2O)5 2+ species. It has been shown that NikA is able to bind nickel and Fe(III)EDTA in the same pocket \n[[cite:PUB00038938]] and that His416 is the only direct metal-protein contact [[cite:PUB00094620]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false} {"text" "<p>Bacterial high affinity transport systems are involved in active transport of solutes across the cytoplasmic membrane. Most of the bacterial ABC (ATP-binding cassette) importers are composed of one or two transmembrane permease proteins, one or two nucleotide-binding proteins and a highly specific periplasmic solute-binding protein. In Gram-negative bacteria the solute-binding proteins are dissolved in the periplasm, while in archaea and Gram-positive bacteria, their solute-binding proteins are membrane-anchored lipoproteins [[cite:PUB00071938], [cite:PUB00071925]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "3mzb", "name" "X-ray structure of NikA in complex with the doubly hydroxylated iron co